Quantum mechanics is a branch of physics that deals with the behavior of matter and energy on a atomic and subatomic level. It is based on the principle that there is a fundamental limit to the amount of information that can be known about a system and that this limit is expressed in terms of the uncertainty principle.

One of the main principles of quantum mechanics is that particles can exist in multiple states or locations at the same time, this is known as superposition. This means that a particle can be in more than one place at the same time, and it is not possible to predict with certainty where the particle will be found.

Another principle of quantum mechanics is the complementary nature of particles, which states that particles can be both waves and particles at the same time. This means that a particle can exhibit properties of both waves and particles, depending on how it is observed.

Quantum mechanics also introduces the concept of probability, which is used to describe the likelihood of an event occurring. This is in contrast to classical mechanics, where events either do or do not occur, with certainty.

Quantum mechanics also predicts the behavior of particles at a distance, meaning particles can interact with each other even if they are far apart. This is known as quantum entanglement, and it is a fundamental property of the universe.
